España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, Spain (España)":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Burgos, Castilla y León, España":"Burgos, Castilla y León, Spanje","Spain":"Spanje"},"en":{"aproximadamente 1225–1304":"about 1225–1304","1225–1304":"1225–1304","–Female":"Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1254–1355":"1254–1355","–1641":"–1641","1205–1250":"1205–1250","1205–1312":"1205–1312","1304":"1304","1205":"1205","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1641":"1641","1355":"1355","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","aproximadamente 1225":"about 1225","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, Spain (España)":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Burgos, Castilla y León, España":"Burgos, Castilla y León, Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Diaz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Manuel, Jesus, Francisco, Jorge, Rafael, Miguel, Pedro, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Díaz</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Didacus</i> (see   Diego  ).","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Diazdeleon","meanings":["Spanish: combination of the surname <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ) and the name León (see   Leon  ) with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Diego","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Francisco, Juan, Fernando, Jose, Miguel, Mario, Maximo, Salvador, Aida, Ana, Domingo.","Spanish: from the very common male personal name <i>Diego</i>, which in the Spanish-speaking world is usually taken to be a shortened form of   Santiago  . However, this may be only a folk etymology. The personal name is found in the Middle Ages in the Latin forms <i>Didacus</i> and <i>Didagus</i>, probably a derivative of Greek <i>didachē</i> ‘doctrine, teaching’. However, in view of the fact that this personal name is unknown outside the Iberian Peninsula, it may actually have a pre-Roman origin."]},{"name":"Diez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Juan, Fernando, Pedro, Rafael, Roberto, Angel, Eduardo, Mario, Ricardo.","Spanish (<b>Díez</b>): variant of <b>Díaz</b> (see   Diaz  ).","German: variant of   Dietz  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cevallos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Juan, Manuel, Pedro, Fernando, Jose, Luis, Eduardo, Francisco, Jaime, Ana, Angel.","Spanish: variant of   Ceballos  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ceballos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Juan, Carlos, Manuel, Francisco, Mario, Sergio, Javier, Jesus, Miguel, Ramon.","Spanish: habitational name from a place called Ceballos in Cantabria. Compare   Cevallos  ,   Zeballos  , and   Zevallos  ."]}]},{"name":"Ordonez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Luis, Juan, Jorge, Manuel, Mario, Jesus, Miguel, Cesar, Javier, Fernando.","Spanish (<b>Ordóñez</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Ordoño</i>, of uncertain origin and meaning."],"variants":[{"name":"Ordones","meanings":["Hispanic (<b>Ordoñes</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Ordóñez</b> (see   Ordonez  )."]},{"name":"Ordoyne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Emile, Eulice, Raoul, Remy.","Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>Ordóñez</b> (see   Ordonez  )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aza","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: habitational name from a place called Aza or Haza in Burgos province. Compare   De Aza  .","Japanese: rare name from Fukushima prefecture usually written 呰 ‘slander’, but the character could be a miswriting of 此口 <b>Konokuchi</b>, another rare name meaning ‘this opening’. Another possibility also pronounced <i>Aza</i> could be 字 ‘(one from a) rural district’."],"variants":[{"name":"De Aza","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Aza  , with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’."]}]},{"name":"Gonzalo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Visigothic: from a personal name formed with <i>gund</i> ‘battle, strife’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gonzalo Diaz de Cevallos y Ordonez de Aza was born about 1225, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain, his father, Diego Ruiz de Ceballos y Gonzalez Giron, was 21 and his mother, Maria Ordoñez de Aza, was 21. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Antolina De La Hoz Y Galindez. He died in 1304, in Burgos, Castilla y León, Spain, at the age of 80."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1225–1304":"umbes 1225–1304","1225–1304":"1225–1304","–Female":"Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1254–1355":"1254–1355","–1641":"–1641","1205–1250":"1205–1250","1205–1312":"1205–1312","1304":"1304","1205":"1205","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1641":"1641","1355":"1355","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","aproximadamente 1225":"umbes 1225","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, Spain (España)":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Burgos, Castilla y León, España":"Burgos, Castilla y León, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"aproximadamente 1225–1304":"noin 1225–1304","1225–1304":"1225–1304","–Female":"Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1254–1355":"1254–1355","–1641":"–1641","1205–1250":"1205–1250","1205–1312":"1205–1312","1304":"1304","1205":"1205","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1641":"1641","1355":"1355","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","aproximadamente 1225":"noin 1225","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, Spain (España)":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Burgos, Castilla y León, España":"Burgos, Castilla y León, Espanja","Spain":"Espanja"},"fr":{"aproximadamente 1225–1304":"e